Chapter VII. Nicaragua

forbidden

Nicaragua is the only country that cannot be crossed despite having diplomatic relations with Haiti. All the power of that country depends on its president. Because of the migrants, Nicaraguan soldiers have work every day. The first time I got to that land was with a group of Cubans. Those kinds of trips have a name of their own. We called it via, derived from the word travel in Spanish. Cubans don't travel frequently with Haitians because they have their own contacts and in fact each nation has its own style of travel,

I must make a parenthesis to explain that there was a Senegalese. They were brave; he had crossed all of Nicaragua on foot, he was very clever in his journey, for in each strategic place he had marked and left a sign thinking—of course—that there might be the possibility of being returned. No doubt he was willing to try again in case, upon arrival in Honduras, he was returned to Costa Rica

.
When they effectively returned it, he took all the other Africans and they took the same path. No Haitian had that degree of courage. The "coyote" that happened to us asked us to be brave and that, if we were not, because we were because we were going to need it, since he would be waiting for us in Honduras, at the other end of Nicaragua, where he would charge us half the payment. The other half of us would get to him with a friend, who would expect our notice that we had already done our part and we would pay him the other half. The coyote told us we were leaving in about four hours. It had taken us days to get to Panama, so those four hours felt like a split second,

He introduced us to three guides to cross-two police bases and to take us to a free place. There were two babies in the group and that caused us concern because it is very easy to be located with the crying of a baby, because the soldiers were never far away in case anyone started crying. That definitely increased nervousness and adrenaline. Since we started walking, we felt closer to Honduras. After about an hour of being on the move, we got to a point very close to the soldiers, but fortunately they didn't see us. Two of them showed up on a motorbike, and we immediately fell to the ground. It is difficult to describe the heaviness that can be felt in these circumstances, the breath agitated by the fear and insecurity that we live in those moments. Only those who live in these circumstances can understand it. I don't think you can imagine the risk we take every day. There are so many dangers in these paths that we traveled suffering from hunger, thirst, ailments, insect bites and extreme physical exhaustion

.
We were on our way almost six hours! And we never got to where we were supposed to, and the worst thing is that there was no sign. Of course we were all more than worried. We got to a point where there was a change of guides. They told us - I want to think that so as not to panic- that all that was part of the plan, that we should continue with the fresh new guides, who would lead us to the connection. Connection means the second part of the road. The Cubans didn't want to change our guidelines, but we were forced to take it because we couldn't stay in the jungle. We continue our route until nightfall. Fear, despair and the desire to see another day grew in our hearts. There were times when every time one had to cross a cornfield, everyone ran, until they reached a wire of iron, but sometimes those iron wires were fed with electric current. And if for some strange reason someone did not have the time to escape, they would have to go out and cross the wires, which would be a very expensive payment for traveling; in addition to risking his life enormously,

After crossing so many fields, we rested in the afternoon; it wasn't even two minutes past when we were attacked by thieves, it turned out that these thieves were the first three guides! In the act we realized that it was them because they had not changed the shirts, they only had handkerchiefs that covered their faces and the thinnest was the easiest to distinguish. The point was that they were "armed to the teeth," with a variety of weapons that included a 9mm, knives and machetes. Two of them were in front, us in the middle and the other behind us. These unscrupulous people used their tactics to sculpt us. Unfortunately they know no respect for anyone, as with women they had no compassion either. With all the nerve and no sightings, they removed their trousers and put their hands up into their underpants. They wanted everything! They didn't care what,

There are thieves and rapists who take as they please every person who crosses their path. Everything that was happening was planned; the other guides went aside, and told us that if anyone followed them, that person would die. Of course we didn't even try to follow them,

The Cubans were too angry, for it wasn't the first time this had happened to them; they had already lost almost everything, just like most. The night was coming and with it the rain, we had nowhere to protect the children with. It was too cold and hard to bear, but we made it one more time. We truly felt that that night God saved us. It can be said that we rested peacefully, because previously we had walked long before we reached the connection. To continue, the guides asked us to take care of our money; we were probably going to give them to him. Of course not! Now more than ever we were trusting, his words were pure lies. In this medium, one must never trust anyone. It's impossible,

Human beings are so cruel, so evil; pure, heartless people, blinded for their own benefit, something depressing. Their justification for keeping the money from us was supposedly to defend it from other assailants, for they would be the only ones not to be sculpted. They wanted to take care of us, if we didn't have anything anymore! So we let them know exactly that, that we were penniless,

Ai get there we asked them to speak on the phone with the person we had hired the trip, to explain what was going on, but he refused. He didn't want to talk to us; said that a portion of the money was missing to make the connection*. We tried to convince him that we would pay him on arrival, but the guides didn't want to talk to us anymore. We were told it would be better to leave him a message and that they would pass it on to him. The contractor of the trip was a thief and was implying that the Haitians had not paid, even though the Cubans had sent him a message telling him that they would pay what was missing. •. . •

We were forced to go on our own. We were very close to the road and noticed that there was traffic and someone could see us. Some cops passed by. After waiting three to four hours, the truck that had to make the connection never arrived and it was past four o'clock in the afternoon. Everyone started worrying about not being able to make the journey and having to spend another night in the jungle. No one had seen where the guides had gone and suddenly a police car arrived. The Cubans, realizing it, ran away. In fact, we all ran except for the women who had babies. It happened that a Haitian friend and a Cuban ran, the cops followed them and we didn't hear from them, we lost track of them,

It could be said that the road had already gone wrong. . So we had to try to get out and see what was going to do-the new strategy. Even though we wanted to stay as a group, one part withdrew, possibly upon the arrival of the police,

We  went to the road, some of us went to bed and two Cubans signaled the cars on the road to try to ask for a ride to bring us closer to the Honduran border, but in reality we were only two hours from Costa Rica. Every time we saw a car we were afraid of being returned to Costa Rica. We were at risk of losing our money and our trip and having to do it again completely, because most of the people who organize the road are thieves. When we started walking, a car in the military took us by surprise. They told us we shouldn't worry, to stay calm. As we went overnight, we'd be back in Costa Rica in the morning. As soon as we got to their base, we saw the rest of the group that had come out of another road. Then the Red Cross fed us and used clothes. We were disappointed that we were unable to reach Honduras, but also happy that we would no longer spend another day in the jungle,

Each had a mat on the floor and we drank from the same water from a well from which soldiers drank. And we made a hole to go to the bathroom, which we shared with the soldiers because there was no bathroom with drainage. It was a Nicaraguan military base; The next morning we were en route to Costa Rica with the soldiers who took us. As soon as we arrived, we went to the address provided by the person who had arranged that route, but to! Denying his house we didn't see anyone, or his dog. We couldn't go to the police because those types of trips weren't allowed. It was a decision we made on our own and we had to take responsibility for it. Every time we sued a travel guide, they stopped him only to calm the group, but then they let him go and take his money. There are some evildoers who pay people to keep an eye on us. Our only hope is that we will all be held accountable to the court at the end of our days,

Thank God, my cell phones hadn't been stolen, only mine. People took me for granted because I was the one who invited them to travel with that man and I didn't have a penny. I'd have to find another way out of Costa Rica with those people to get my peace of mind,

The same day I started my failed journey was a friend who invited me to travel with him inside a container; I rejected him because I trusted my original plan, but mine had failed and his had been successful. This friend put me in touch with the same truck driver to try to convince him to arrange another trip. I was afraid because I knew beforehand that some people had died in those boxes, but this driver was different,

The container had a big hole coming down the truck to get the air in it, and my job was to gather about thirty people. If we got people together, me and my friends could travel for free. But 'imagine!, who would have confidence in you immediately after having organized a failed journey? However, they also knew that the driver was always successful on his travels and our trip was scheduled for Sunday. "

About me, I gathered more than forty people for Sunday's departure. Everyone was impatient, but the driver called us and told us he couldn't that Sunday and had to wait for the next one. I couldn't make any kind of claim because I had an empty pocket, but some who no longer had patience took another route; some successfully and some not; and when they came back they said, "Yes, I knew, I should have waited."Days passed super slow and we had little patience. To tell you the truth, we were filled with impatience, with discontent; because nothing seemed to be going right. When Sunday finally arrived, I didn't even have time to eat because I focused on bringing people together on the list and others that I had added. At our meeting point, near a gas station, I had to collect the money and pay half the total for everyone, and the rest when we got there. My important things went inside a suitcase with the driver,There were people who threatened me if we came back, telling me they'd beat me. But my team and I talked often about the chances of that happening if we didn't succeed. We organized step by step, cautiously. The driver didn't work 'alone, there was another driver with him backing up and some guides, because we had cjue crossing a lake on foot and that would take about four hours. We start the road at 4:00 p. M. I noticed that the guides had firearms, if necessary. That time I felt like everything was going to be okay. On this occasion, strange as it may seem, I felt a certainty that everything was going to be okay and that there was going to be no trouble,Every day would be the same tasks. One had to walk for hours before making the connection, pass ingenuity wires and other things. We spent the night at the house of one of the guides to hydrate before switching to another group of guides, who were part of the plan. We made the change in the middle of nowhere. We only heard the birds and the wind pinking the branches of the trees. Sometimes we wonder why we made so many sacrifices, but we already know the answer. We are human and the isolation is stronger than us,After many hours of walking in the middle of the jungle we were getting to the point of connection. When we were given the indication of getting on the container, we started running like crazy, hit each other. Once everyone was inside the container, the driver provided us all with water for the trip. We had to stay silent until we got to Honduras. The trip was faster than we thought, because we left at eight o'clock at night and arrived at four in the morning. The experience in the container was wonderful because we didn't see anything. from the outside. You can say it was a sense of relief. We just had to wait for the driver to give us the signal to get us off. And when we go down, we walked about an hour before crossing the Nicaraguan border to reach Honduras. Blessed God, we had made it. Everything went well. Despite all the sorrows we went through along the way, in the end God showed us a way out. All the way,After months of misery going through the jungle, suffering physically and emotionally, we never hope to get to Honduras. All this was really a test of survival and thank God we came out afloat. Some said the road began in Honduras, because only two countries, Guatemala and Mexico, were missing to reach our destination, which was the United States of America. Honduras was one of the countries that accepted Haitians without problem, while in Panama we had to say that we were African. In Honduras they knew well that we were Haitians, who came from Brazil, Chile, Ecuador, Venezuela and elsewhere. When we got there, we arrived dirty, tired and hungry. All we wanted immensely was first to bathe, eat and rest; Most of us didn't have any clothes. It was very nice to see how we all shared what we had,

closer to the target and calmer. You could even say that we wanted to continue the adventure because in Honduras we had no pressure, everything was calm,

