Chapter VIII. Honduras

Imminent

In Honduras we could rent a hotel, but we preferred to rent an apartment, because in a hotel we could not cook and we did not have much money. We weren't looking for comfort, but a basic need,

We knew in advance that we should not waste any more time; everything had to be planned correctly, as we had done since we left Brazil. The reason for our urgency was that President Obama's term was going to end soon. We were aware of the news, of the political sacy for power that was being lived in the United States. We mistakenly think that when this president is there, he would give us political asylum without problem and open the doors for our benefit. Nothing further from reality, because the benefit was not for everyone. Obama was one of the presidents who made the most deportations during his tenure. At the time, the elections between the two candidates were very closed and we knew their political tendencies. They knew that if Donald Trump won, things wouldn't turn out in our favor,

When we get to! apartment we rented, we took a bath and saw how to move to buy food. Until that time there were six Haitians. I didn't have a cell phone thanks to the thieves who left me incommunicado. I had to buy one so I could' be in contact with my mother, who cared about me. But first /we had to change, because we already had time in the same clothes and needed to go and buy something new. However, despite what we thought we would do, we relaxed for a few minutes, had some beers and listened, music. We talked about our experiences in. these months. By that time we had. 'already three months of touring,

I had talked about going for a walk, dancing, meeting people and having fun; but because we were so tired and the night was very long, we fell asleep. '

In the morning, when we woke up we had to go in search of a Haitian who had more time there, because for some reason he stayed in the country. They had passed on their data to us, for already many who had crossed knew him. He was the only one who could explain to us how the situation was in the migration offices. We felt some anxiety and didn't want to waste time, but we didn't want to go too fast either. Some Haitians who arrived a week before us took us to a place to buy cheap clothes and cell phones. I wanted to talk to my mom because that day was her birthday, on November 28th. I got $500 for a trip. I managed to join a group so I could buy my cell phone and call my mother to congratulate her,

We went to a market to buy things to cook and you can say we had a pretty nice and relaxed day. At night we were all in a mood, the weather was good and we were going to enjoy that space. It's funny how you learn to enjoy things only in situations like these. When human beings have everything, sometimes they don't enjoy it. However, we every space we had tried to have a good time. We didn't know how many days we were going to stay and we wanted to take things easy, take our time; because after leaving everything changed. We started—with insecurities, with fears, we dealt with all kinds of thoughts and feelings, stress returned and to suffer the same and other needs.

we drank beer in one of the squares, which was badly seen by Hondurans because they don't drink beer on the street, but out of ignorance we did. We didn't know it was forbidden in the country. We had no knowledge of that rule. After a few moments two policemen arrived and asked us to follow them to the delegation and when we arrived they asked us for papers to return to Nicaragua, because what we were doing was illegal. We tried various forms of negotiation. We begged them to let us go, but they wouldn't take the deal,

we told them that if we were to be returned to Nicaragua we would have to start over, but now without money because we no longer had and our family was not in a position to help us. It was a terrible situation and a disgrace to our families if they found out that the police had handcuffed us because of taking in the street. So, we started to see how else we could get rid of and avoid being returned. Within the group was a friend who spoke perfect Spanish, so much so that the inspector was impressed by his fluency. And in the end. the inspector told us that we could leave conditioned; warned us that the next day we should leave the country, . if they were not going to report us to the migration offices for the same situation. They caught us with a cooler full of beer and they had it. Very carefully, before we retired we dared to ask them to continue in the apartment, but they told us no, that those beers had already changed ownership,

When we came to the apartment none of us commented on it, because it was a bad experience, even if for us it was something insignificant. Although we had already scared the way, we feared being returned to Nicaragua, because it is one of the worst countries we're going through. For us it was an unnecessary experience,

in the morning we prepared to leave the country, because of the agreement we made with the police. By eight o'clock in the morning we were already on migration and we were given an appointment for two o'clock in the afternoon. We returned to the house to cook and prepare to leave and at one o'e we return to wait for the truck. It was a special truck, because in some countries that we were going through migration, he advised taxis to charge us twice as much. For us it was no problem because what we wanted was to keep going. When we were in the truck it was 1:30 and it was like three people missing. The driver just didn't feel like waiting for others and when you pay for the ticket and you don't arrive, you lose the money. We talked to the driver, but he wouldn't agree. At least we tried. It really wasn't that important to us. Unfortunately one has to think selfishly and do anything above whoever it is to defend his person and follow the goal. The others stayed and we go on. We wanted to turn the leaf io as fast as possible and continue to leave Honduras, for on second thought, it was not so pleasant to be there,

At the time of the trip, everyone was joking with the impatience to discover another land. In every country we were going to cross fortunately we found a friend, family member or acquaintance who had already gone through that experience. So, they explained to us how we should pass, who we had to pay or if we could pass directly. When we arrived at The Guatemalan border in the early morning, we followed the instructions so that no one would steal our personal things. We knew beforehand that we would meet fake guides, fake taxi drivers, as well as people on the street that we distrusted, because they always wanted to take money from us. Rarely were we lucky not to pay. This time we paid to go to migration, which was in a market,

As  Cubans paid a lot of money to cross the border, abusive guides made them cross a hill to get more money out of them, while we were allowed to cross directly. As we got on the cab that would lead us to the border, the taxi driver told us that we could all cross there. Without much thought, at that time we paid the taxi driver five dollars more to provide us with information. It's amazing how people give so much value to money and where there's money can be corrupted, no time firm lycreated. Very, but very few people gave us anything without asking for anything in return,

The truck had very loud music and as we walked the streets of Guatemala all 'world looked at us, as if they had never seen people of color, or maybe it was what they saw us with admiration, I would like to think it was the second. It was a strange thing that sometimes people when they saw us thought we were Americans and they wanted to speak us in English. Which suggests that they had no idea what kind of migration had reached that border. We looked at the road and realized it looked like the periphery,

