Chapter IX. Guatemala

StopGuatemala, for us it was one of the fastest trips. When the taxi driver left us in front of the migration offices, we realized that it wasn't really the migration office. Within a public market was an office to receive migrants, in which we obtained a document valid for twenty days, although we were not supposed to stay in the city more than twenty-four hours after obtaining it.while we were waiting for the bus we looked for a bathroom to brush our teeth and a restaurant to eat. We were scrambled with the Cubans, who had also made the route as a group. While we were enlisting, a lady came to offer us coffee. She was a religious lady with a big heart, who then fed us all and made a long, beautiful prayer with us. We sat down and talked to her, it was a blessing. He felt empathy for us, for he let us know that he was aware of the suffering we had gone through, we were passing and we would still pass. It was extremely rare for someone to put the moment in our shoes, no one had done it until that time. It was as if I'd been watching those humiliations we went through. It was so beautiful the feeling. that brought us, to the point that we couldn't hide our tears. We were at a break point,. as the Bible says, as a fragile glass. We can read in •Revelation 21:4, Queen Valera version (1960): "God will wipe all tears from their eyes; And there will be no more death, no more crying, no crying, no pain; because the first things happened." One more episode had already ended. We missed seeing someone showing compassion and acceptance. ';> 1She gave us her help, although she did not have many resources, so we were very satisfied with how little she was able to do. Very few people had welcomed us - until then - in such a way. She could not stay with us for long; would have been very good for his company, as we had more hours left to wait for the bus. The lady promised she'd be back tomorrow if God wanted to. And so I would do it every day to help other groups of migrants, because they kept arriving every morning at about the same time. But it wasn't more than half a day before we took our route to Mexico,as soon as the buses arrived, we lined up to wait for a call by name to take our places. There were three buses that were to carry about 150 people. As soon as we were all on the bus, the cops performed a check, to see that everything was fine. There were some who didn't pay and those who barely had enough money to do it,There was not a day when we didn't think the authorities or the "coyotes" would abuse rios, because they shouldn't have taken us to a ground transport terminal nail; we could have bought the tickets ourselves, but that didn't have so much because we already wanted to get out of that country and move on to the next,The truck finally got going for. get to the capital, and from there we had to take another to get to the Mexican border. We spent a few hours on the short trip, we couldn't rest because the bus, river. it was very comfortable,During the trip, on the bus we talked about the possibility of living in Mexico and about the option of deportation. They were things we thought about all the time. We couldn't stop having those thoughts. Impossible to stop the mind in circumstances like this. Paulo Coelho said: "The possibility of realized a dream is 1st that makes life interesting". Our mind played a fundamental role in this journey. One definitely had a responsibility to tame thoughts; because it could be helpful to keep your mind free, but not in the difficult and embarrassing circumstances we go through, where if you don't have it tamed, you can lose control and end up crazy. This same author said that when someone wants something they should know that they are taking risks and that's why life is worth it. It didn't matter in the end where it would end, whether in the United States or Mexico; I already felt like a winner just by getting to either of those two places alive. The risk was worth it.

We arrived in the capital of Guatemala at night, close to where migration was. We thought we were going to be able to sleep, but soon we'd continue the route. We just had to do the paperwork and print and photocopy the necessary documents to be there. Everyone told us that with that paper we could stay twenty days in the country—how, how if you were interested in staying one second longer.Therefore we thank you for your hospitality and head to the truck terminal to buy our tickets. When we arrived everything was closed. In Guatemala the bus has no nightlife as in certain countries that we had passed, and we could not buy anything. At the last minute we saw a street vendor selling frying, but the point was that she didn't want to accept dollars. We explained that we were tourists, a story that helped him change his mind. I didn't have much to eat, but that would be enough for us to get to Mexico,As soon as we could we split up to buy our tickets, and the ticket seller wanted to charge us—the very abusive one—twice the price, which we didn't accept and told him we'd wait for someone else to give us the normal price, we were sick of so much abuse and impunity. The price of the trip was ten dollars and he wanted to charge us twenty. What they were unaware of was that we were aware of the prices, almost everything, because those who had already passed had explained to us step by step their experience, costs, prices, everything. We didn't ignore the real cost. So he, realizing that we knew the price, told us to get on the bus,Unfortunately, every country we crossed had its own weaponry of evil; we were ranted, we were charged dearly for food, water, taxis, dollar change, physical, verbal abuse, and yet we were able to continue on our way.At five o'clock in the morning we were arriving at the Guatemala-Mexico border. At this border taxis were bicycles with a cabin that could carry three people maximum. We were told that we could not cross without first going through the Mexican customs to have the visa, that we had to pass over a river and they knew that we could not refuse it, not really we all had a passport. We concentrated on the riverbank, which we had to cross on a raft. Unfortunately everything was charged in dollar, something inconsibly and inexplicable,

